            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Maya Lin Erickson is a product of two worlds. Raised in Berkeley by her Swedish-American architect father and Taiwanese immigrant mother, her childhood home was a blend of minimalist design and the fragrant aroma of her mother's cooking. From her father, she inherited a love for form and creative expression; from her mother, a quiet pragmatism and a deep sense of duty. This duality defined her, but it was her younger brother, Leo, who shaped her path. Born with a severe speech impediment, Leo communicated his vibrant inner world primarily through drawing. Maya, just a few years older, learned that a shared piece of paper and a box of crayons could bridge the silence, becoming their most profound language.\n\nThis discovery became her calling. After completing a double major in Psychology and Art at UC Santa Cruz, she pursued a Master's in Art Therapy. She felt a pull back to the Bay Area, but this time to San Francisco itself, a city she saw as the region's complex, beating heart. With her new degree, she secured a position working for a non-profit that provides therapeutic services to children in under-resourced schools and community clinics.\n\nNow, Maya\u2019s life is a carefully budgeted existence in the Inner Richmond. She shares a classic bay window apartment with a software engineer, a friendship that provides a daily, amicable clash of cultures between San Francisco's tech and non-profit sectors. Her commute is a 3.8-mile journey on the 38-Geary bus, a time she uses for reflection, sketching fellow passengers in a small notebook. Her days are emotionally demanding, navigating the complex worlds of her young clients, but she finds solace in long, foggy runs through Golden Gate Park and quiet afternoons at the de Young Museum.\n\nMaya dreams of eventually opening a small, private practice focused on adolescents, creating a safe space for them to process their lives through art. She hopes to one day afford a small condo in the city she now calls home, a tangible piece of the community she works so hard to support. For Maya, success isn't a stock option; it's the breakthrough moment when a quiet child finally picks up a paintbrush and shows her their world."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was eight, sitting on the warm wood floor of their Berkeley home. Leo, silent as ever, furiously scribbled with a green crayon. He pushed the paper towards her: a towering, magnificent dragon with smoke curling from its nostrils. In that moment, seeing the power and frustration he couldn't speak, she understood. Art wasn't just pictures; it was a voice. That shared understanding became the foundation of her life, a silent promise to help others find their own language on paper. This memory occurred during her early childhood.\n\n2.\nHer first solo visit to the de Young Museum after starting her masters. She stood in a quiet gallery, caught between a stark, minimalist painting and an ancient, intricately carved jade vessel. In that moment, she saw her father\u2019s love for clean lines and her mother\u2019s deep, resilient history reflected back at her. The two halves of her heritage, which had often felt separate, clicked into place as a single, beautiful identity. It affirmed her path, blending art and psychology. This occurred in her early twenties.\n\n3.\nIt was her first week working at the clinic. A seven-year-old boy, Francisco, had not spoken a word. After three sessions of just sitting with him, he finally picked up a blue marker. He drew a small boat alone on a vast, stormy sea. Maya\u2019s heart ached with recognition. She didn't need him to speak; he had shown her everything. The memory cemented her purpose, a visceral reminder that her quiet, patient work could provide a life raft. This happened shortly after she moved to San Francisco.\n\n4.\nAfter a brutal day listening to stories of neglect, she went for a run. The fog in Golden Gate Park was so thick she could barely see the path. The damp chill clung to her skin, and the world dissolved into a soft, grey silence. With only the sound of her own breathing and footsteps on the trail, the weight of the day began to lift, absorbed by the mist. This run became her ritual, a way the city itself helped heal her. This is a recurring memory from her adult life.\n\n5.\nThe first night in her Inner Richmond apartment, her roommate was out. She stood at the large bay window, watching the 38-Geary bus hiss to a stop below as fog softened the streetlights. The scent of her neighbor's cooking drifted up; it wasn't her mother's, but it was comfort all the same. A profound sense of quiet ownership settled over her. This wasn't her parents' house or a temporary dorm. It was hers. This was home. This memory is from when she first secured her apartment."
